title: [convict] Fix header
body:
The DefinitelyTyped header needs to have the name of the library as it is published on npm and must not have a patch number in the version.

The types-publisher package determines the name of the library a type definition describes [by calling `parseHeaderOrFail`][publisher-extract], which is provided by [the definitelytyped-header-parser library][header-parser]. Looking at its source, one can see that it gets the library name [by parsing the `Type definitions for` comment line][call parselabel]. As [a comment in the code describes][parselabel], it parses the line in reverse, first finding the version number and then assuming that the rest is the name of the library. Unfortunately, in the case of convict, the name was incorrect. While, [unlike with bunyan][bunyan], it appears to have published automatically, there is no guarantee that that will continue to function.

Additionally, when the header is parsed in strict mode, [the version number must be bare (i.e. not prefixed by `v`) and only have major and minor version numbers][version]. Patch numbers are not allowed.

See also #17045.

title: material-ui: Fix error in typescript@next
body:
Was getting this error:
```ts
material-ui-tests.tsx(323,45): error TS2345: Argument of type '(props: { label: string; muiTheme?: MuiTheme; }) => Element' is not assignable to parameter of type 'ComponentClass<{}> | StatelessComponent<{}>'.
  Type '(props: { label: string; muiTheme?: MuiTheme; }) => Element' is not assignable to type 'StatelessComponent<{}>'.
    Types of parameters 'props' and 'props' are incompatible.
      Type '{ children?: ReactNode; }' is not assignable to type '{ label: string; muiTheme?: MuiTheme; }'.
        Property 'label' is missing in type '{ children?: ReactNode; }'.
```

I think the problem is that we handle callbacks covariantly now, while previously it was bivariant and you could treat `{}` as a `{ label: string; muiTheme?: MuiTheme }`.

body:

However, declaring both `forEach(action: (item: T) => void): void` and `forEach(action: (item: T, index: number) => void): void` is unnecessary since the second overload encompasses the first. So I have switched both `List` and `Enumerable` to using just that overload.
Note: this assumes that `List` really does provide the `index` parameter.
CC @KamyarNazeri

body:
Currently only strings and numbers are allowed as types when using `react-intl`'s `formatMessage` or `formatHTMLMessage` methods.

`react-intl`'s API Wiki defines the value for `values` property as `object` (https://github.com/yahoo/react-intl/wiki/API#intlshape), which means that you should be able to pass the method any kind of data inside of an object.

Using `object` seems to be banned by `tslint` in this project, so changed the code to allow `boolean`, `date`, `number` and `string` as usable values.

title: [rethinkdb] Fix connection options of SSL
body:
According to the rethinkdb nodejs driver source code:
https://github.com/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/blob/v2.3.3/drivers/javascript/net.coffee#L160-L171

```coffeescript
        # Configuration options for enabling an SSL connection
        # Allows the ability to pass in all the options as specified in
        # [tls.connect](https://nodejs.org/api/tls.html#tls_tls_connect_options_callback)
        # or just true  in case the client wants ssl but the server
        # is using a certificate with a valid verified chain and there
        # is no need to specify certificates on the client
        if typeof host.ssl is 'boolean' && host.ssl
            @ssl = {}
        else if typeof host.ssl is 'object'
            @ssl = host.ssl
        else
            @ssl = false
```

https://github.com/rethinkdb/rethinkdb/blob/v2.3.3/drivers/javascript/net.coffee#L952-L957

```coffeescript
        if @ssl
          @ssl.host = @host
          @ssl.port = @port
          @rawSocket = tls.connect @ssl
        else
          @rawSocket = net.connect @port, @host
```

it should allow to input all `tls.connect` options instead of only `ca: []`.
